        "explanation": "अद्वैत (Advaita, literally 'non-dual') Vedanta, primarily systematized by Adi Shankaracharya, teaches that there is only ONE ultimate reality - ब्रह्म (Brahman). This is a trap because many confuse Advaita with other Vedantic schools or assume it's about 'oneness' in a simplistic sense. The core insights are: (1) ब्रह्म सत्यम् (Brahman alone is real); (2) जगत् मिथ्या (The world is apparent/illusory, not ultimately real); (3) जीवो ब्रह्मैव नापरः (The individual soul is none other than Brahman). The apparent duality we experience is due to अविद्या (ignorance/Maya). Through ज्ञान (knowledge), one realizes तत्त्वमसि ('That Thou Art') - the identity of आत्मन् (individual self) with ब्रह्म (universal Self). This is NOT pantheism (everything is God) or monism (reducing everything to one substance), but rather non-dualism - the negation of duality itself. Understanding this distinction is crucial for grasping Vedantic metaphysics!"
